n class=\"mord mtight\">25</span></span></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.23em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"frac-line\" style=\"border-bottom-width:0.04em;\"></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.394em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">1</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.345em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mclose nulldelimiter\"></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">+</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.123em;\"></span><span class=\"minner\">…</span></span></span></span></p><p><strong>Partial sums</strong>:</p><ul>\n<li>First 10 terms: ≈ 1.5498</li>\n<li>First 100 terms: ≈ 1.6350</li>\n<li>First 1000 terms: ≈ 1.6439</li>\n</ul><p>The series converges slowly to π²/6 ≈ 1.6449340668...</p><p><strong>Euler's proof (1734)</strong>: Euler used a brilliant technique involving the Fourier series for x². He showed:</p><p><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msubsup><mo>∑</mo><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∞</mi></msubsup><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msup><mi>n</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msup><mi>π</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mn>6</mn></mfrac></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\sum_{n=1}^{\\infty} \\frac{1}{n^2} = \\frac{\\pi^2}{6}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.1901em;vertical-align:-0.345em;\"></span><span class=\"mop\"><span class=\"mop op-symbol small-op\" style=\"position:relative;top:0em;\">∑</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8043em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.4003em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">n</span><span class=\"mrel mtight\">=</span><span class=\"mord mtight\">1</span></span></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.2029em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">∞</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.2997em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mopen nulldelimiter\"></span><span class=\"mfrac\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8451em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.655em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">n</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.7463em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.786em;margin-right:0.0714em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.5em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size3 size1 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.23em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"frac-line\" style=\"border-bottom-width:0.04em;\"></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.394em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">1</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.345em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mclose nulldelimiter\"></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.3629em;vertical-align:-0.345em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mopen nulldelimiter\"></span><span class=\"mfrac\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:1.0179em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.655em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">6</span></span></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.23em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"frac-line\" style=\"border-bottom-width:0.04em;\"></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.394em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">π</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8913em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.931em;margin-right:0.0714em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.5em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size3 size1 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.345em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mclose nulldelimiter\"></span></span></span></span></span></p><p>This was one of the first major results in analytic number theory and established Euler's reputation.</p><p><strong>Verification</strong>:\n<span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mfrac><msup><mi>π</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mn>6</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>9.8696</mn><mn>6</mn></mfrac><mo>≈</mo><mn>1.6449</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\frac{\\pi^2}{6} = \\frac{9.8696}{6} \\approx 1.6449</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.3629em;vertical-align:-0.345em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mopen nulldelimiter\"></span><span class=\"mfrac\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:1.0179em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.655em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">6</span></span></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.23em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"frac-line\" style=\"border-bottom-width:0.04em;\"></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.394em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">π</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8913em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.931em;margin-right:0.0714em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.5em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size3 size1 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.345em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mclose nulldelimiter\"></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.1901em;vertical-align:-0.345em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mopen nulldelimiter\"></span><span class=\"mfrac\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8451em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.655em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">6</span></span></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.23em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"frac-line\" style=\"border-bottom-width:0.04em;\"></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.394em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">9.8696</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.345em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mclose nulldelimiter\"></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">≈</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1.6449</span></span></span></span></p><p>This matches our numerical calculation. ✓</p><h3 class=\"markdown-h2\">Part B: Zeros and the Prime Number Theorem</h3><p>The <strong>Prime Number Theorem</strong> states:\n<span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>π</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>∼</mo><mfrac><mi>x</mi><mrow><mi>ln</mi><mo>⁡</mo><mi>x</mi></mrow></mfrac></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\pi(x) \\sim \\frac{x}{\\ln x}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">π</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">∼</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.0404em;vertical-align:-0.345em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mopen nulldelimiter\"></span><span class=\"mfrac\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.6954em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.655em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mop mtight\"><span class=\"mtight\">l</span><span class=\"mtight\">n</span></span><span class=\"mspace mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.1952em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">x</span></span></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.23em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"frac-line\" style=\"border-bottom-width:0.04em;\"></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.394em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">x</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.345em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mclose nulldelimiter\"></span></span></span></span></span></p><p>More precisely:\n<span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>π</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>=</mo><mtext>li</mtext><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>+</mo><mi>E</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\pi(x) = \\text{li}(x) + E(x)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">π</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">li</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">+</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">E</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span></p><p>where li(x) is the logarithmic integral and E(x) is the error term.</p><p><strong>Connection to zeros</strong>: The error term E(x) can be expressed as a sum over the non-trivial zeros ρ of ζ(s):</p><p><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>E</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>=</mo><msub><mo>∑</mo><mi>ρ</mi></msub><mfrac><msup><mi>x</mi><mi>ρ</mi></msup><mi>ρ</mi></mfrac></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">E(x) = \\sum_{\\rho} \\frac{x^\\rho}{\\rho}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">E</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.3921em;vertical-align:-0.4811em;\"></span><span class=\"mop\"><span class=\"mop op-symbol small-op\" style=\"position:relative;top:0em;\">∑</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.0017em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.4003em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">ρ</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.4358em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mopen nulldelimiter\"></span><span class=\"mfrac\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.911em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.655em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">ρ</span></span></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.23em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"frac-line\" style=\"border-bottom-width:0.04em;\"></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.394em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">x</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.7385em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.931em;margin-right:0.0714em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.5em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size3 size1 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">ρ</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.4811em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mclose nulldelimiter\"></span></span></span></span></span></p><p>The real part of ρ determines how fast terms grow:</p><ul>\n<li>If Re(ρ) = 1/2, then <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∣</mi><msup><mi>x</mi><mi>ρ</mi></msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∣</mi><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>x</mi><mrow><mn>1</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">/</mi><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">|x^\\rho| = x^{1/2}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">∣</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.6644em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">ρ</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mord\">∣</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.888em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.888em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">1/2</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>, giving error <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>O</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><msqrt><mi>x</mi></msqrt><mi>log</mi><mo>⁡</mo><mi>x</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">O(\\sqrt{x} \\log x)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.0503em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02778em;\">O</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord sqrt\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8003em;\"><span class=\"svg-align\" style=\"top:-3em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\" style=\"padding-left:0.833em;\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span></span></span><span style=\"top:-2.7603em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"hide-tail\" style=\"min-width:0.853em;height:1.08em;\"><svg xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" width=\"400em\" height=\"1.08em\" viewBox=\"0 0 400000 1080\" preserveAspectRatio=\"xMinYMin slice\"><path d=\"M95,702\nc-2.7,0,-7.17,-2.7,-13.5,-8c-5.8,-5.3,-9.5,-10,-9.5,-14\nc0,-2,0.3,-3.3,1,-4c1.3,-2.7,23.83,-20.7,67.5,-54\nc44.2,-33.3,65.8,-50.3,66.5,-51c1.3,-1.3,3,-2,5,-2c4.7,0,8.7,3.3,12,10\ns173,378,173,378c0.7,0,35.3,-71,104,-213c68.7,-142,137.5,-285,206.5,-429\nc69,-144,104.5,-217.7,106.5,-221\nl0 -0\nc5.3,-9.3,12,-14,20,-14\nH400000v40H845.2724\ns-225.272,467,-225.272,467s-235,486,-235,486c-2.7,4.7,-9,7,-19,7\nc-6,0,-10,-1,-12,-3s-194,-422,-194,-422s-65,47,-65,47z\nM834 80h400000v40h-400000z\"></path></svg></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.2397em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mop\">lo<span style=\"margin-right:0.01389em;\">g</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span></li>\n<li>If Re(ρ) > 1/2, terms grow faster, giving larger errors</li>\n</ul><p><strong>Riemann Hypothesis implies</strong>:\n<span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>π</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>=</mo><mtext>li</mtext><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>+</mo><mi>O</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><msqrt><mi>x</mi></msqrt><mi>log</mi><mo>⁡</mo><mi>x</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\pi(x) = \\text{li}(x) + O(\\sqrt{x} \\log x)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">π</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">li</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">+</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.0503em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02778em;\">O</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord sqrt\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8003em;\"><span class=\"svg-align\" style=\"top:-3em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\" style=\"padding-left:0.833em;\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span></span></span><span style=\"top:-2.7603em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"hide-tail\" style=\"min-width:0.853em;height:1.08em;\"><svg xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" width=\"400em\" height=\"1.08em\" viewBox=\"0 0 400000 1080\" preserveAspectRatio=\"xMinYMin slice\"><path d=\"M95,702\nc-2.7,0,-7.17,-2.7,-13.5,-8c-5.8,-5.3,-9.5,-10,-9.5,-14\nc0,-2,0.3,-3.3,1,-4c1.3,-2.7,23.83,-20.7,67.5,-54\nc44.2,-33.3,65.8,-50.3,66.5,-51c1.3,-1.3,3,-2,5,-2c4.7,0,8.7,3.3,12,10\ns173,378,173,378c0.7,0,35.3,-71,104,-213c68.7,-142,137.5,-285,206.5,-429\nc69,-144,104.5,-217.7,106.5,-221\nl0 -0\nc5.3,-9.3,12,-14,20,-14\nH400000v40H845.2724\ns-225.272,467,-225.272,467s-235,486,-235,486c-2.7,4.7,-9,7,-19,7\nc-6,0,-10,-1,-12,-3s-194,-422,-194,-422s-65,47,-65,47z\nM834 80h400000v40h-400000z\"></path></svg></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.2397em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mop\">lo<span style=\"margin-right:0.01389em;\">g</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span></p><p>This is the <strong>sharpest possible error bound</strong>. RH thus guarantees primes are distributed as uniformly as possible, with no hidden patterns causing large deviations.</p><p><strong>Without RH</strong>: The error could be much larger, meaning our understanding of prime distribution would be less precise.</p><h3 class=\"markdown-h2\">Part C: Computational Verification Is Not Proof</h3><p>As of 2025, over <strong>10 trillion non-trivial zeros</strong> have been verified to lie on the critical line Re(s) = 1/2. All verified zeros satisfy RH.</p><p><strong>Why this isn't a proof</strong>:</p><ol>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Infinite cases remain</strong>: The zeta function has infinitely many zeros. Checking even trillions leaves infinitely many unverified.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Counterexamples can appear late</strong>: History shows conjectures can fail beyond computational reach:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Pólya's conjecture</strong> (1919): Believed true for n &#x3C; 906,150,257 but false beyond</li>\n<li><strong>Skewes' number</strong>: The smallest n where li(n) > π(n) is astronomically large</li>\n<li><strong>Mertens conjecture</strong>: Believed true for n &#x3C; <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>14</mn></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">10^{14}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8141em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\">0</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8141em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">14</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> but disproved in 1985</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Mathematics requires deductive proof</strong>: Observing a pattern, even in trillions of cases, doesn't explain why it holds. A proof provides understanding and certainty.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>RH could be false for a sparse set</strong>: Perhaps only one in 10¹⁰⁰ zeros violates RH — beyond any feasible computation but still disproving the hypothesis.</p>\n</li>\n</ol><p>Computational evidence strongly supports RH, but mathematical truth demands proof for all cases.</p><h3 class=\"markdown-h2\">Part D: Generalised Riemann Hypothesis</h3><p>The <strong>Generalised Riemann Hypothesis (GRH)</strong> extends RH to <strong>Dirichlet L-functions</strong>:</p><p><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>L</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>s</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>χ</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>=</mo><msubsup><mo>∑</mo><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∞</mi></msubsup><mfrac><mrow><mi>χ</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>n</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><msup><mi>n</mi><mi>s</mi></msup></mfrac></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">L(s, \\chi) = \\sum_{n=1}^{\\infty} \\frac{\\chi(n)}{n^s}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">L</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">s</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">χ</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.355em;vertical-align:-0.345em;\"></span><span class=\"mop\"><span class=\"mop op-symbol small-op\" style=\"position:relative;top:0em;\">∑</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8043em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.4003em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">n</span><span class=\"mrel mtight\">=</span><span class=\"mord mtight\">1</span></span></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.2029em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">∞</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.2997em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mopen nulldelimiter\"></span><span class=\"mfrac\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:1.01em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.655em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">n</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.5935em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.786em;margin-right:0.0714em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.5em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size3 size1 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">s</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.23em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"frac-line\" style=\"border-bottom-width:0.04em;\"></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.485em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">χ</span><span class=\"mopen mtight\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">n</span><span class=\"mclose mtight\">)</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.345em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mclose nulldelimiter\"></span></span></span></span></span></p><p>where χ is a Dirichlet character (a completely multiplicative periodic function).</p><p><strong>GRH statement</strong>: All non-trivial zeros of L(s, χ) have real part 1/2.</p><p>This generalises RH (which is the case χ = 1, the trivial character).</p><p><strong>Implications of GRH</strong>:</p><ol>\n<li><strong>Primality testing</strong>: Miller-Rabin test becomes deterministic and polynomial-time</li>\n<li><strong>Primes in arithmetic progressions</strong>: Sharp error bounds for primes ≡ a (mod m)</li>\n<li><strong>Cryptography</strong>: Certain hardness assumptions become provable</li>\n<li><strong>Algorithmic number theory</strong>: Many algorithms conditional on GRH become unconditional</li>\n</ol><p><strong>Examples</strong>:</p><ul>\n<li><strong>Deterministic primality testing</strong> in time <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>O</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><msup><mrow><mi>log</mi><mo>⁡</mo></mrow><mn>6</mn></msup><mi>n</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">O(\\log^6 n)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.1484em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02778em;\">O</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mop\"><span class=\"mop\">lo<span style=\"margin-right:0.01389em;\">g</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8984em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.1473em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">6</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">n</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> (currently AKS algorithm is proven but slower)</li>\n<li><strong>Factoring</strong>: Improved bounds for trial division strategies</li>\n<li><strong>Class number computations</strong>: Fast algorithms for computing class numbers</li>\n</ul><p><strong>Current status</strong>: GRH is widely believed true. Many results in number theory are proven \"assuming GRH\". If GRH were false, it would invalidate hundreds of conditional theorems and algorithms.</p><h3 class=\"markdown-h2\">Why RH Matters</h3><p>The Riemann Hypothesis is central to mathematics because:</p><ol>\n<li><strong>Primes are fundamental</strong>: Understanding their distribution is key to number theory</li>\n<li><strong>Connects fields</strong>: Links analysis, number theory, and algebra</li>\n<li><strong>Practical impact</strong>: Influences cryptography and algorithms</li>\n<li><strong>Deep mystery</strong>: Its truth reveals hidden order in the primes</li>\n</ol><p><strong>Prize</strong>: $1,000,000 Millennium Prize for proof or disproof</p><p><strong>History</strong>: Proposed by Bernhard Riemann in 1859, it remains unsolved after 166 years. It is considered one of the most important open problems in all of mathematics.</p></div></details>","rawContent","\n# The Zeta Function\n\nThe **Riemann zeta function** ζ(s) is defined for complex numbers s with real part > 1 as:\n\n$$\\zeta(s) = \\sum_{n=1}^{\\infty} \\frac{1}{n^s} = \\frac{1}{1^s} + \\frac{1}{2^s} + \\frac{1}{3^s} + \\ldots$$\n\n**Examples**:\n- ζ(2) = 1 + 1/4 + 1/9 + 1/16 + ... = π²/6 ≈ 1.645\n- ζ(3) = 1 + 1/8 + 1/27 + 1/64 + ... ≈ 1.202 (Apéry's constant)\n- ζ(4) = π⁴/90 ≈ 1.082\n\nThrough **analytic continuation**, ζ(s) can be extended to all complex numbers except s = 1 (where it has a pole).\n\n# Connection to Primes\n\nThe zeta function connects deeply to prime numbers through Euler's product formula:\n\n$$\\zeta(s) = \\prod_{p \\text{ prime}} \\frac{1}{1 - p^{-s}}$$\n\nThis identity reveals that the distribution of primes controls the behaviour of ζ(s).\n\n# Zeros of the Zeta Function\n\nThe zeta function ζ(s) has zeros at:\n1. **Trivial zeros**: s = -2, -4, -6, -8, ... (all negative even integers)\n2. **Non-trivial zeros**: Complex numbers with real part between 0 and 1\n\nThe non-trivial zeros control the error term in the Prime Number Theorem.\n\n# The Hypothesis\n\n**Riemann Hypothesis (1859)**: All non-trivial zeros of ζ(s) have real part equal to 1/2.\n\nIn other words, all non-trivial zeros lie on the **critical line** Re(s) = 1/2.\n\nThis is one of the **Millennium Prize Problems** with a $1,000,000 reward for a proof.\n\n# The Challenge\n\n**Part A**: Compute ζ(2) by summing the series. Verify Euler's result that ζ(2) = π²/6.\n\n**Part B**: Explain why the location of zeta zeros affects the accuracy of the Prime Number Theorem. What does the Riemann Hypothesis tell us about how closely π(x) approximates x/ln(x)?\n\n**Part C**: The first few non-trivial zeros occur at approximately s = 1/2 + 14.13i, 1/2 + 21.02i, 1/2 + 25.01i. All verified zeros (over 10 trillion of them) lie exactly on the critical line. Why doesn't this computational evidence constitute a proof?\n\n**Part D**: Research the **Generalised Riemann Hypothesis (GRH)**. What broader class of functions does it apply to, and what would its proof imply for computational number theory?\n\n:::hint\nFor Part A, Basel problem was solved by Euler in 1734. The connection to π² involves Fourier series.\n:::\n\n:::hint\nFor Part B, the error term in the Prime Number Theorem is connected to how far zeros are from the critical line.\n:::\n\n:::hint\nFor Part C, consider that mathematical truth requires proof for all cases, not just many cases. Counterexamples to conjectures have appeared beyond computational reach.\n:::\n\n:::hint\nGRH concerns Dirichlet L-functions, which generalise the zeta function. Many algorithms assume GRH for polynomial-time complexity.\n:::\n\n:::solution\n**Answer**: A) Calculation sketch below, π²/6 ≈ 1.645. B) Zeros control error oscillations; RH implies tight error bounds. C) Computational evidence doesn't prove all zeros satisfy the property. D) GRH applies to Dirichlet L-functions; its truth would prove many conditional results in algorithms and number theory.\n\n## Part A: Computing ζ(2)\n\nThe series:\n$$\\zeta(2) = \\sum_{n=1}^{\\infty} \\frac{1}{n^2} = 1 + \\frac{1}{4} + \\frac{1}{9} + \\frac{1}{16} + \\frac{1}{25} + \\ldots$$\n\n**Partial sums**:\n- First 10 terms: ≈ 1.5498\n- First 100 terms: ≈ 1.6350\n- First 1000 terms: ≈ 1.6439\n\nThe series converges slowly to π²/6 ≈ 1.6449340668...\n\n**Euler's proof (1734)**: Euler used a brilliant technique involving the Fourier series for x². He showed:\n\n$$\\sum_{n=1}^{\\infty} \\frac{1}{n^2} = \\frac{\\pi^2}{6}$$\n\nThis was one of the first major results in analytic number theory and established Euler's reputation.\n\n**Verification**:\n$$\\frac{\\pi^2}{6} = \\frac{9.8696}{6} \\approx 1.6449$$\n\nThis matches our numerical calculation. ✓\n\n## Part B: Zeros and the Prime Number Theorem\n\nThe **Prime Number Theorem** states:\n$$\\pi(x) \\sim \\frac{x}{\\ln x}$$\n\nMore precisely:\n$$\\pi(x) = \\text{li}(x) + E(x)$$\n\nwhere li(x) is the logarithmic integral and E(x) is the error term.\n\n**Connection to zeros**: The error term E(x) can be expressed as a sum over the non-trivial zeros ρ of ζ(s):\n\n$$E(x) = \\sum_{\\rho} \\frac{x^\\rho}{\\rho}$$\n\nThe real part of ρ determines how fast terms grow:\n- If Re(ρ) = 1/2, then $|x^\\rho| = x^{1/2}$, giving error $O(\\sqrt{x} \\log x)$\n- If Re(ρ) > 1/2, terms grow faster, giving larger errors\n\n**Riemann Hypothesis implies**:\n$$\\pi(x) = \\text{li}(x) + O(\\sqrt{x} \\log x)$$\n\nThis is the **sharpest possible error bound**. RH thus guarantees primes are distributed as uniformly as possible, with no hidden patterns causing large deviations.\n\n**Without RH**: The error could be much larger, meaning our understanding of prime distribution would be less precise.\n\n## Part C: Computational Verification Is Not Proof\n\nAs of 2025, over **10 trillion non-trivial zeros** have been verified to lie on the critical line Re(s) = 1/2. All verified zeros satisfy RH.\n\n**Why this isn't a proof**:\n\n1. **Infinite cases remain**: The zeta function has infinitely many zeros. Checking even trillions leaves infinitely many unverified.\n\n2. **Counterexamples can appear late**: History shows conjectures can fail beyond computational reach:\n   - **Pólya's conjecture** (1919): Believed true for n < 906,150,257 but false beyond\n   - **Skewes' number**: The smallest n where li(n) > π(n) is astronomically large\n   - **Mertens conjecture**: Believed true for n < $10^{14}$ but disproved in 1985\n\n3. **Mathematics requires deductive proof**: Observing a pattern, even in trillions of cases, doesn't explain why it holds. A proof provides understanding and certainty.\n\n4. **RH could be false for a sparse set**: Perhaps only one in 10¹⁰⁰ zeros violates RH — beyond any feasible computation but still disproving the hypothesis.\n\nComputational evidence strongly supports RH, but mathematical truth demands proof for all cases.\n\n## Part D: Generalised Riemann Hypothesis\n\nThe **Generalised Riemann Hypothesis (GRH)** extends RH to **Dirichlet L-functions**:\n\n$$L(s, \\chi) = \\sum_{n=1}^{\\infty} \\frac{\\chi(n)}{n^s}$$\n\nwhere χ is a Dirichlet character (a completely multiplicative periodic function).\n\n**GRH statement**: All non-trivial zeros of L(s, χ) have real part 1/2.\n\nThis generalises RH (which is the case χ = 1, the trivial character).\n\n**Implications of GRH**:\n\n1. **Primality testing**: Miller-Rabin test becomes deterministic and polynomial-time\n2. **Primes in arithmetic progressions**: Sharp error bounds for primes ≡ a (mod m)\n3. **Cryptography**: Certain hardness assumptions become provable\n4. **Algorithmic number theory**: Many algorithms conditional on GRH become unconditional\n\n**Examples**:\n- **Deterministic primality testing** in time $O(\\log^6 n)$ (currently AKS algorithm is proven but slower)\n- **Factoring**: Improved bounds for trial division strategies\n- **Class number computations**: Fast algorithms for computing class numbers\n\n**Current status**: GRH is widely believed true. Many results in number theory are proven \"assuming GRH\". If GRH were false, it would invalidate hundreds of conditional theorems and algorithms.\n\n## Why RH Matters\n\nThe Riemann Hypothesis is central to mathematics because:\n\n1. **Primes are fundamental**: Understanding their distribution is key to number theory\n2. **Connects fields**: Links analysis, number theory, and algebra\n3. **Practical impact**: Influences cryptography and algorithms\n4. **Deep mystery**: Its truth reveals hidden order in the primes\n\n**Prize**: $1,000,000 Millennium Prize for proof or disproof\n\n**History**: Proposed by Bernhard Riemann in 1859, it remains unsolved after 166 years. It is considered one of the most important open problems in all of mathematics.\n:::\n","dynamicBlocks",[]]
